                              <!-- Body -->
                              <div class="media-body article-info bucket-margin margin-24-bottom clearfix">
                                  <a class="unskinned display-inline-block eyebrow-link margin-4-bottom" href="https://time.com/world/">
                                    <div class="category heading-eyebrow">
                                      World
                                    </div>
                                  </a>
                            
                                <h3 class="headline heading-3 heading-content margin-8-bottom media-heading">
                                  <a href="/5741805/us-cryptocurrency-expert-north-korea/">
                                      U.S. Says Cryptocurrency Expert Violated North Korea Sanctions
                                  </a>
                                </h3>
                            
                                <div class="article-info-extended">
                            
                            
                                  <!-- Not using summary because of conflicting styles -->
                            
                                  <!-- Summary/Dek -->
                            
                                </div>
                            
                            
                              </div>
                            </article>
                          </div>
                <p>She said North Korea will respond with its own harsh language if Trump again uses similar phrases and shows that he is intentionally provoking North Korea.</p>
                <p>&ldquo;If any language and expressions stoking the atmosphere of confrontation are used once again &#8230; that must really be diagnosed as the relapse of the dotage of a dotard,&rdquo; Choe said.</p>
                <p>On Wednesday, the North&rsquo;s military chief, Pak Jong Chon, also warned that the use of force against the North would cause a &ldquo;horrible&rdquo; consequence for the U.S. He said North Korea would take unspecified &ldquo;prompt corresponding actions at any level&rdquo; if the U.S. takes any military action.</p>
                <p>During a visit to London on Tuesday, Trump said his relationship with Kim was &ldquo;really good&rdquo; but also called for him to follow up on a commitment to denuclearize.</p>
                <p>&ldquo;We have the most powerful military we ever had, and we are by far the most powerful country in the world and hopefully we don&rsquo;t have to use it. But if we do, we will use it,&rdquo; Trump said.</p>
                  
                    <div
                         id="ad-300x250_m_1" 
                        data-tgxtrack="true" data-tgxtargeting="%7B%7D" data-tgxupdatecorrelator="true" 
                      class="ad ad-container ad-wrapper type-300x250 instream-ad mobile-ad"
                      data-dimensions="300x250" role="complementary" aria-hidden="true"></div>
                
                  
                    <div
                         id="ad-728x90_LL_td_1" 
                        data-tgxtargeting="%7B%7D" data-tgxlazy="200"
                      class="ad ad-container ad-wrapper type-728x90 instream-ad tablet-ad desktop-ad x2"
                      data-dimensions="728x90" role="complementary" aria-hidden="true"></div>
                
                <p>Kim, Trump added, &ldquo;likes sending rockets up, doesn&rsquo;t he? That&rsquo;s why I call him rocket man.&rdquo;</p>
                <p>In 2017, Trump and Kim traded threats of destruction as North Korea carried out a slew of high-profile weapons tests aimed at acquiring an ability to launch nuclear strikes on the U.S. mainland. Trump said he would rain &ldquo;fire and fury&rdquo; on North Korea and derided Kim as &ldquo;little rocket man,&rdquo; while Kim questioned Trump&rsquo;s sanity and said he would &#8220;tame the mentally deranged U.S. dotard with fire.&rdquo;</p>
                <p>The two leaders have avoided such words and developed better relations after North Korea entered nuclear negotiations with the U.S. last year. Trump even said he and Kim &ldquo;fell in love.&rdquo;</p>
                <p>Kim and Trump have met three times, starting with a summit in Singapore in June 2018. But their nuclear diplomacy has remained largely deadlocked since their second meeting in Vietnam in February ended without any deal due to disputes over U.S.-led sanctions on North Korea.</p>
                <p class="author-feedback-text"><strong>Contact us</strong> at <a href="mailto:editors@time.com?subject=(READER FEEDBACK) North Korea Threatens to Resume Calling Trump a &#039;Dotard&#039;" target="_self" rel="noopener noreferrer">editors@time.com</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>


